h>\n|<math>\\sqrt{\\frac{\\alpha^4\\alpha_G}{4 \\pi}}</math>\n|<math>\\frac{\\sqrt{\\alpha^4\\alpha_G}}{4 \\pi}</math>\n|<math>\\frac{\\sqrt{\\alpha^5\\alpha_G}}{4 \\pi}</math>\n|<math>\\frac{\\alpha}{4 \\pi}</math>\n|<math>\\frac{\\alpha}{4 \\pi}</math>\n|<math>\\frac{\\alpha^2}{4\\pi}</math>\n|<math>\\frac{\\alpha^2 m_\\text{e}}{4 \\pi}</math>\n|<math>\\frac{\\alpha^2 m_\\text{e}}{4 \\pi}</math>\n|<math>\\frac{\\alpha^2}{4\\pi \\mu}</math>\n|<math>\\frac{\\alpha^2}{4\\pi \\mu}</math>\n|<math>\\frac{\\alpha^2}{4\\pi \\mu}</math>\n|-\n|[[Stefan\u2013Boltzmann constant]] <br> <math>\\sigma = \\frac{\\pi^2 k_\\text{B}^4}{60 \\hbar^3 c^2} \\,</math>\n|<math>\\frac{\\pi^2}{60} \\,</math>\n|<math>\\frac{\\pi^2}{60} \\,</math>\n|<math>\\frac{\\pi^2}{60} \\,</math>\n|<math>\\frac{\\pi^2 \\alpha^3}{60} \\,</math>\n|<math>\\frac{\\pi^2 \\alpha^2}{60} \\,</math>\n|<math>\\frac{\\pi^2 \\alpha^2}{240} \\,</math>\n|<math>\\frac{\\pi^2}{60} \\,</math>\n|<math>\\frac{\\pi^2}{60} \\,</math>\n|<math>\\frac{\\pi^2}{60} \\,</math>\n|<math>\\frac{\\pi^2}{60} \\,</math>\n|<math>\\frac{\\pi^2}{60} \\,</math>\n|<math>\\frac{\\pi^2}{60} \\,</math>\n|}\n\nwhere:\n*{{math|''\u03b1''}} is the [[fine-structure constant]], {{sfrac|''k<sub>e</sub>e''<sup>2</sup>|''\u0127c''}} = {{math|{{resize|150%|(}}{{sfrac|''e''|''q''<sub>Planck</sub>}}{{resize|150%|)}}{{su|p=2}} \u2248 (137.035999){{sup|\u22121}}}}\n*{{math|''\u03b1''{{sub|''G''}}}} is the [[gravitational coupling constant]], {{sfrac|''Gm<sub>e</sub>''<sup>2</sup>|''\u0127c''}} = {{math|{{resize|150%|(}}{{sfrac|''m''{{sub|e}}|''m''{{sub|Planck}}}}{{resize|150%|)}}{{su|p=2}} \u2248 {{val|1.7518|e=-45}}}}\n*{{math|''\u00b5''}} is the [[proton-to-electron mass ratio]], {{sfrac|''m{{sub|p}}''|''m{{sub|e}}''}} \u2248 {{math|{{val|1836.15267247}}}}\n\n==Notation and use==\n\nNatural units are most commonly used by ''setting the units to one''. For example, many natural unit systems include the equation {{math|1=''c'' = 1}} in the unit-system definition, where {{math|''c''}} is the [[speed of light]]. If a velocity {{math|''v''}} is half the speed of light, then as {{math|1=''v'' = {{sfrac|''c''|2}}}} and {{math|1=''c'' = 1}}, hence {{math|1=''v'' = {{sfrac|1|2}}}}. The equation {{math|1=''v'' = {{sfrac|1|2}}}} means \"the velocity {{math|''v''}} has the value one-half when measured in Planck units\", or \"the velocity {{math|''v''}} is one-half the Planck unit of velocity\".\n\nThe equation {{math|1=''c'' = 1}} can be plugged in anywhere else. For example, Einstein's equation {{math|1=''E'' = ''mc''<sup>2</sup>}} can be rewritten in Planck units as {{math|1=''E'' = ''m''}}. This equation means \"The energy of a particle, measured in Planck units of energy, equals the mass of the particle, measured in Planck units of mass.\"\n\n=== Advantages and disadvantages ===\nCompared to [[SI]] or other unit systems, natural units have both advantages and disadvantages:\n\n*'''Simplified equations:''' By setting constants to 1, equations containing those constants appear more compact and in some cases may be simpler to understand. For example, the [[invariant mass|special relativity]] equation {{math|1=''E''<sup>2</sup> = ''p''<sup>2</sup>''c''<sup>2</sup> + ''m''<sup>2</sup>''c''<sup>4</sup>}} appears somewhat complicated, but the natural units version, {{math|1=''E''<sup>2</sup> = ''p''<sup>2</sup> + ''m''<sup>2</sup>}}, appears simpler.\n*'''Physical interpretation:''' Space and time are put on equal footing and are both measured in the same units. Natural unit systems automatically subsume [[dimensional analysis]]. For example, in [[Planck units]], the units are defined by properties of quantum mechanics and gravity. Not coincidentally, the Planck unit of length is approximately the distance at which [[quantum gravity]] effects become important. Likewise, [[atomic units]] are based on the mass and charge of an electron, and not coincidentally the atomic unit of length is the [[Bohr radius]] describing the \"orbit\" of the electron in a [[hydrogen atom]].\n*'''No prototypes:''' A [[Prototype#Metrology|prototype]] is a physical object that defines a unit, such as the [[International Prototype of the Kilogram]], a physical cylinder of metal whose mass used to be by definition exactly one [[kilogram]] (as of 2019 one kilogram is instead defined [[2019 redefinition of the SI base units|in terms of fundamental constants]]). A prototype definition always has imperfect reproducibility between different places and between different times, and it is an advantage of natural unit systems that they use no prototypes. (They share this advantage with some ''non-natural'' unit systems, such as [[conventional electrical units]].)\n*'''Less precise measurements:''' [[SI]] units are designed to be used in precision measurements. For example, the [[second]] is defined by an atomic transition frequency in cesium atoms, because this transition frequency can be precisely reproduced with [[atomic clock]] technology. Natural unit systems are generally ''not'' based on quantities that can be precisely reproduced in a lab. Therefore, in order to retain the same degree of precision, the fundamental constants used still have to be measured in a laboratory in terms of physical objects that can be directly observed. If this is not possible, then a quantity expressed in natural units can be less precise than the same quantity expressed in SI units. For example, Planck units use the [[gravitational constant|gravitational constant {{math|''G''}}]], which is measurable in a laboratory only to four significant digits.\n\n==Choosing constants to normalize==\nOut of the many [[physical constant]]s, the designer of a system of natural unit systems must choose a few of these constants to normalize (set equal to 1). It is not possible to normalize just ''any'' set of constants. For example, the mass of a proton and the mass of an electron cannot both be normalized: if the mass of an electron is defined to be 1, then the mass of a proton has to be approximately 1836. In a less trivial example, the [[fine-structure constant]], {{math|''\u03b1'' \u2248 {{sfrac|137}}}}, cannot be set to 1 because it is a dimensionless number defined in terms of other quantities. The fine-structure constant is related to other physical constants through {{math|''\u03b1'' {{=}} {{sfrac|''k''{{sub|e}}''e''{{sup|2}}|''\u0127c''}}}}, where {{math|''k''{{sub|e}}}} is the [[Coulomb constant]], {{math|''e''}} is the [[elementary charge]], {{math|''\u0127''}} is the [[reduced Planck constant]], and {{math|''c''}} is the [[speed of light]]. Thus, it is impossible to set all of {{math|''k''{{sub|e}}}}, {{math|''e''}}, {{math|''\u0127''}}, and {{math|''c''}} to 1; at most three of this set can be normalized to 1.\n\n==Electromagnetism units==\n{{main|Lorentz\u2013Heaviside units|Gaussian units}}\nIn [[SI units]], electric charge is expressed in coulombs, a separate unit which is additional to the \"mechanical\" units (mass, length, time), even though the traditional definition of the ampere refers to some of these other units.\n\nIn order to build natural units in electromagnetism one can use:\n*'''[[Lorentz\u2013Heaviside units]]''' (classified as a '''rationalized''' system of electromagnetism units).\n*'''[[Gaussian units]]''' (classified as a '''non-rationalized''' system of electromagnetism units).\nOf these, Lorentz\u2013Heaviside is somewhat more common,<ref name=\"GreinerNeise1995\">{{cite book|author1=Walter Greiner|author2=Ludwig Neise|author3=Horst St\u00f6cker|title=Thermodynamics and Statistical Mechanics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=12DKsFtFTgYC&pg=PA385|year=1995|publisher=Springer-Verlag|isbn=978-0-387-94299-5|page=385}}</ref> mainly because [[Maxwell's equations]] are simpler in Lorentz\u2013Heaviside units than they are in Gaussian units.\n\nIn the two unit systems, the Planck unit charge {{math|''q''<sub>P</sub>}} is:\n*{{math|''q''<sub>P</sub> {{=}} {{sqrt|4\u03c0''\u03b1\u0127c''}}}} (Lorentz\u2013Heaviside),\n*{{math|''q''<sub>P</sub> {{=}} {{sqrt|''\u03b1\u0127c''}}}} (Gaussian)\nwhere {{math|''\u0127''}} is the [[reduced Planck constant]], {{math|''c''}} is the [[speed of light]], and {{math|''\u03b1'' \u2248 {{sfrac|137.036}}}} is the [[fine-structure constant]].\n\nIn a natural unit system where {{math|1=[[speed of light|''c'']] = 1}}, Lorentz\u2013Heaviside units can be derived from SI units by setting {{math|1=[[electric constant|''\u03b5''<sub>0</sub>]] = [[magnetic constant|''\u03bc''<sub>0</sub>]] = 1}}. Gaussian units can be derived from SI units by a more complicated set of transformations, such as multiplying all [[electric field]]s by {{math|(4\u03c0''\u03b5''<sub>0</sub>)<sup>\u2212{{frac|2}}</sup>}}, multiplying all [[magnetic susceptibility|magnetic susceptibilities]] by {{math|4\u03c0}}, and so on.<ref>See [[Gaussian units#General rules to translate a formula]] and references therein.</ref>\n\n==Systems of natural units==\n\n===Planck units===\n{{Main|Planck units}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" align=\"right\" style=\"margin-left: 1em; background-color: #ffffff\"\n! Quantity\n! Expression\n! Metric value\n! Name\n|- align=\"left\"\n| rowspan=2|[[Length]] (L)\n| <math>l_\\text{P} = \\sqrt{4 \\pi \\hbar G \\over c^3}</math> ([[Lorentz\u2013Heaviside units|L\u2013H]])\n| {{val|5.729|e=-35|u=m}}\n| rowspan=2|[[Planck length]]\n|-\n| <math>l_\\text{P} = \\sqrt{\\hbar G \\over c^3}</math> ([[Gaussian units|G]] and original)\n| {{val|1.616|e=-35|u=m}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2|[[Mass]] (M)\n| <math>m_\\text{P} = \\sqrt{\\hbar c \\over 4 \\pi G}</math> ([[Lorentz\u2013Heaviside units|L\u2013H]])\n| {{val|6.140|e=-9|u=kg}}\n| rowspan=2|[[Planck mass]]\n|-\n| <math>m_\\text{P} = \\sqrt{\\hbar c \\over G}</math> ([[Gaussian units|G]] and original)\n| {{val|2.176|e=-8|u=kg}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2|[[Time]] (T)\n| <math>t_\\text{P} = \\sqrt{4 \\pi \\hbar G \\over c^5} </math> ([[Lorentz\u2013Heaviside units|L\u2013H]])\n| {{val|1.911|e=-43|u=s}}\n| rowspan=2|[[Planck time]]\n|-\n| <math>t_\\text{P} = \\sqrt{\\hbar G \\over c^5} </math> ([[Gaussian units|G]] and original)\n| {{val|5.391|e=-44|u=s}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2|[[Temperature]] (\u0398)\n| <math>T_\\text{P} = \\sqrt{\\frac{\\hbar c^5}{4 \\pi G {k_\\text{B}}^2}}</math> ([[Lorentz\u2013Heaviside units|L\u2013H]])\n| {{val|3.997|e=31|u=K}}\n| rowspan=2|[[Planck temperature]]\n|-\n| <math>T_\\text{P} = \\sqrt{\\frac{\\hbar c^5}{G {k_\\text{B}}^2}}</math> ([[Gaussian units|G]] and original)\n| {{val|1.417|e=32|u=K}}\n|-\n| rowspan=3|[[Electric charge]] (Q)\n| <math>q_\\text{P} = e</math> (original)\n| {{val|1.602|e=-19|u=C}}\n| rowspan=3|[[Planck charge]]\n|-\n| <math>q_\\text{P} = \\sqrt{\\hbar c \\epsilon_0}</math> ([[Lorentz\u2013Heaviside units|L\u2013H]])\n| {{val|5.291|e=-19|u=C}}\n|-\n| <math>q_\\text{P} = \\sqrt{\\hbar c (4 \\pi \\epsilon_0)}</math> ([[Gaussian units|G]])\n| {{val|1.876|e=-18|u=C}}\n|}\n\nPlanck units are defined by\n:{{math|1=''c'' = ''\u0127'' = ''G'' = ''k''{{sub|e}} = ''k''{{sub|B}} = 1}},\nwhere {{math|''c''}} is the [[speed of light]], {{math|''\u0127''}} is the [[reduced Planck constant]], {{math|''G''}} is the [[gravitational constant]], {{math|''k''{{sub|e}}}} is the [[Coulomb constant]], and {{math|''k''<sub>B</sub>}} is the [[Boltzmann constant]].\n\nPlanck units are a system of natural units that is not defined in terms of properties of any prototype, physical object, or even [[elementary particle]]. They only refer to the basic structure of the laws of physics: {{math|''c''}} and {{math|''G''}} are part of the structure of [[spacetime]] in [[general relativity]], and {{math|''\u0127''}} captures the relationship between energy and frequency which is at the foundation of [[quantum mechanics]]. This makes Planck units particularly useful and common in theories of [[quantum gravity]], including [[string theory]].\n\nPlanck units may be considered \"more natural\" even than other natural unit systems discussed below, as Planck units are not based on any arbitrarily chosen prototype object or particle. For example, some other systems use the mass of an electron as a parameter to be normalized. But the electron is just one of 16 known massive [[elementary particle]]s, all with different masses, and there is no compelling reason, within fundamental physics, to emphasize the electron mass over some other elementary particle's mass.\n\nPlanck considered only the units based on the universal constants ''G'', ''\u0127'', ''c'', and ''k''<sub>B</sub> to arrive at natural units for [[length]], [[time]], [[mass]], and [[temperature]].<ref name=\"TOM\">*Tomilin, K. A., 1999, \"[http://old.ihst.ru/personal/tomilin/papers/tomil.pdf Natural Systems of Units: To the Centenary Anniversary of the Planck System]\", 287\u2013296.</ref> Planck did not adopt any electromagnetic units. However, since the [[Gaussian units#\"Rationalized\" unit systems|non-rationalized]] gravitational constant, ''G'', is set to 1, a natural extension of Planck units to a unit of [[electric charge]] is to also set the non-rationalized Coulomb constant, ''k''<sub>e</sub>, to 1 as well (as well as the Stoney units).<ref name=\"PAV\">{{cite book|last=Pav\u0161ic|first=Matej|title=The Landscape of Theoretical Physics: A Global View|volume=119|year=2001|publisher=Kluwer Academic|location=Dordrecht|isbn=978-0-7923-7006-2|pages=347\u2013352|url=https://www.springer.com/gp/book/9781402003516#otherversion=9780792370062|series=Fundamental Theories of Physics | doi = 10.1007/0-306-47136-1 |arxiv=gr-qc/0610061}}</ref> This is the non-rationalized Planck units (Planck units with the Gaussian version), which is more convenient but not rationalized, there is also a Planck system which is rationalized (Planck units with the Lorentz-Heaviside version), set 4{{pi}}''G'' and ''\u03b5''<sub>0</sub> (instead of ''G'' and ''k''<sub>e</sub>) to 1, which may be less convenient but is rationalized. Another convention is to use the [[elementary charge]] as the basic unit of [[electric charge]] in the Planck system.<ref name=\"Tolin1999\">{{cite journal | title=Fine-structure constant and dimension analysis | author=Tomilin, K. | journal=Eur. J. Phys. | year=1999 | volume=20 | issue=5 | pages=L39\u2013L40 | doi=10.1088/0143-0807/20/5/404|bibcode = 1999EJPh...20L..39T | url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/1a874406c6f191a4b18d3e7f30657ff6faa25ca4 }}</ref> Such a system is convenient for [[black hole]] physics. The two conventions for unit charge differ by a factor of the square root of the [[fine-structure constant]]. Planck's paper also gave numerical values for the base units that were close to modern values.\n\nThe original Planck units are based on [[Gaussian units]], thus <math>G=k_e=1</math> and thus <math>\\epsilon_0=\\frac{1}{4 \\pi}</math> and <math>\\mu_0=4 \\pi</math>. However, the Planck units can also be based on [[Lorentz\u2013Heaviside units]], thus <math>G=k_e=\\frac{1}{4 \\pi}</math> and <math>\\epsilon_0=\\mu_0=Z_0=1</math> (this is often called '''rationalized Planck units''', e.g. the rationalized [[Planck energy]]). Both conventions of Planck units set <math>c=\\hbar=k_B=1</math>.\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Stoney units===\n{{main|Stoney units}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" align=\"right\" style=\"margin-left: 1em; background-color: #ffffff\"\n! Quantity\n! Expression\n! Metric value\n|- align=\"left\"\n| [[Length]] (L)\n| <math>l_\\text{S} = \\sqrt{\\frac{G k_\\text{e} e^2}{c^4}}</math>\n| {{val|1.38068|e=-36|u=m}}\n|-\n| [[Mass]] (M)\n| <math>m_\\text{S} = \\sqrt{\\frac{k_\\text{e} e^2}{G}}</math>\n| {{val|1.85921|e=-9|u=kg}}\n|-\n| [[Time]] (T)\n| <math>t_\\text{S} = \\sqrt{\\frac{G k_\\text{e} e^2}{c^6}} </math>\n| {{val|4.60544|e=-45|u=s}}\n|-\n| [[Temperature]] (\u0398)\n| <math>T_\\text{S} = \\sqrt{\\frac{c^4 k_\\text{e} e^2}{G {k_\\text{B}}^2}}</math>\n| {{val|1.21028|e=31|u=K}}\n|-\n| [[Electric charge]] (Q)\n| <math>q_\\text{S} = e \\ </math>\n| {{val|1.60218|e=-19|u=C}}\n|}\n\nStoney units are defined by:\n:{{math|1=''c'' = ''G'' = ''k''{{sub|e}} = ''e'' = ''k''{{sub|B}} = 1}},\nwhere {{math|''c''}} is the [[speed of light]], {{math|''G''}} is the [[gravitational constant]], {{math|''k''{{sub|e}}}} is the [[Coulomb constant]], {{math|''e''}} is the [[elementary charge]], and {{math|''k''<sub>B</sub>}} is the [[Boltzmann constant]].\n\n[[George Johnstone Stoney]] was the first physicist to introduce the concept of natural units. He presented the idea in a lecture entitled \"On the Physical Units of Nature\" delivered to the [[British Association]] in 1874.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Ray | first = T.P. | year=1981 | title=Stoney's Fundamental Units | journal=Irish Astronomical Journal | volume=15 | page=152|bibcode = 1981IrAJ...15..152R }}</ref> Stoney units differ from Planck units by fixing the [[elementary charge]] at 1, instead of the [[Planck constant]] (only discovered after Stoney's proposal).\n\nStoney units are rarely used in modern physics for calculations, but they are of historical interest.\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Atomic units===\n{{Main|Atomic units}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" align=\"right\" style=\"margin-left: 1em; background-color: #ffffff\"\n! Quantity\n! Expression\n! Metric value\n|- align=\"left\"\n| [[Length]] (L)\n| <math>l_\\text{A} = \\frac{\\hbar^2 (4 \\pi \\epsilon_0)}{m_\\text{e} e^2}</math> (both Hartree and Rydberg)\n| {{val|5.292|e=-11|u=m}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2|[[Mass]] (M)\n| <math>m_\\text{A} = m_\\text{e} \\ </math> (Hartree)\n| {{val|9.109|e=-31|u=kg}}\n|-\n| <math>m_\\text{A} = 2 m_\\text{e} \\ </math> (Rydberg)\n| {{val|1.822|e=-30|u=kg}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2|[[Time]] (T)\n| <math>t_\\text{A} = \\frac{\\hbar^3 (4 \\pi \\epsilon_0)^2}{m_\\text{e} e^4} </math> (Hartree)\n| {{val|2.419|e=-17|u=s}}\n|-\n| <math>t_\\text{A} = \\frac{2 \\hbar^3 (4 \\pi \\epsilon_0)^2}{m_\\text{e} e^4} </math> (Rydberg)\n| {{val|4.838|e=-17|u=s}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2|[[Temperature]] (\u0398)\n| <math>T_\\text{A} = \\frac{m_\\text{e} e^4}{\\hbar^2 (4 \\pi \\epsilon_0)^2 k_\\text{B}}</math> (Hartree)\n| {{val|3.158|e=5|u=K}}\n|-\n| <math>T_\\text{A} = \\frac{m_\\text{e} e^4}{2 \\hbar^2 (4 \\pi \\epsilon_0)^2 k_\\text{B}}</math> (Rydberg)\n| {{val|1.579|e=5|u=K}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2|[[Electric charge]] (Q)\n| <math>q_\\text{A} = e \\ </math> (Hartree)\n| {{val|1.602|e=-19|u=C}}\n|-\n| <math>q_\\text{A} = \\frac{e}{\\sqrt{2}} \\ </math> (Rydberg)\n| {{val|1.133|e=-19|u=C}}\n|}\n\nThere are two types of atomic units, closely related.\n\n'''Hartree atomic units''':\n:{{math|1=''e'' = ''m''{{sub|e}} = ''\u0127'' = ''k''{{sub|e}} = ''k''{{sub|B}} = 1}}\n:{{math|1=''c'' = {{sfrac|''\u03b1''}}}}\n'''Rydberg atomic units''':<ref>{{Cite book\n  | last = Turek\n  | first = Ilja\n  | title = Electronic structure of disordered alloys, surfaces and interfaces\n  | publisher = Springer\n  | year = 1997\n  | edition = illustrated\n  | pages = 3\n  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=15wz64DPVqAC&pg=PA3\n  | isbn =978-0-7923-9798-4\n  }}</ref>\n:{{math|1={{sfrac|''e''|{{sqrt|2}}}} = 2''m''{{sub|e}} = ''\u0127'' = ''k''{{sub|e}} = ''k''{{sub|B}} = 1}}\n:{{math|1=''c'' = {{sfrac|2|''\u03b1''}}}}\n\nCoulomb's constant is generally expressed as \n:{{math|1=''k''{{sub|e}} = {{sfrac|4\u03c0''\u03b5''{{sub|0}}}}}}.\n\nThese units are designed to simplify atomic and molecular physics and chemistry, especially the [[hydrogen atom]], and are widely used in these fields. The Hartree units were first proposed by [[Douglas Hartree]], and are more common than the Rydberg units.\n\nThe units are designed especially to characterize the behavior of an electron in the ground state of a hydrogen atom. For example, using the Hartree convention, in the [[Bohr model]] of the hydrogen atom, an electron in the ground state has orbital velocity = 1, orbital radius = 1, angular momentum = 1, [[ionization energy]] = {{sfrac|2}}, etc.\n\nThe unit of [[energy]] is called the [[Hartree energy]] in the Hartree system and the [[Rydberg energy]] in the Rydberg system. They differ by a factor of 2. The [[speed of light]] is relatively large in atomic units (137 in Hartree or 274 in Rydberg), which comes from the fact that an electron in hydrogen tends to move much slower than the speed of light. The [[gravitational constant]] is extremely small in atomic units (around 10<sup>\u221245</sup>), which comes from the fact that the gravitational force between two electrons is far weaker than the [[Coulomb force]]. The unit length, {{math|''l''<sub>A</sub>}}, is the [[Bohr radius]], {{math|''a''<sub>0</sub>}}.\n\nThe values of {{math|''c''}} and {{math|''e''}} shown above imply that {{math|1=''e'' = {{sqrt|''\u03b1\u0127c''}}}}, as in [[Gaussian units]], ''not'' [[Lorentz\u2013Heaviside units]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Relativistic Quantum Chemistry: The Fundamental Theory of Molecular Science |first=Markus |last=Reiher |first2=Alexander |last2=Wolf |page=7 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YwSpxCfsNsEC&pg=PA7 |isbn=9783527627493 |date=2009-05-13 }}</ref> However, hybrids of the Gaussian and Lorentz\u2013Heaviside units are sometimes used, leading to inconsistent conventions for magnetism-related units.<ref>[http://info.phys.unm.edu/~ideutsch/Classes/Phys531F11/Atomic%20Units.pdf ''A note on units'' lecture notes]. See the [[atomic units]] article for further discussion.</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Quantum chromodynamics (QCD) units===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" align=\"right\" style=\"margin-left: 1em; background-color: #ffffff\"\n! Quantity\n! Expression\n! Metric value\n|- align=\"left\"\n| [[Length]] (L)\n| <math>l_{\\mathrm{QCD}} = \\frac{\\hbar}{m_\\text{p} c}</math>\n| {{val|2.103|e=-16|u=m}}\n|-\n| [[Mass]] (M)\n| <math>m_{\\mathrm{QCD}} = m_\\text{p} \\ </math>\n| {{val|1.673|e=-27|u=kg}}\n|-\n| [[Time]] (T)\n| <math>t_{\\mathrm{QCD}} = \\frac{\\hbar}{m_\\text{p} c^2}</math>\n| {{val|7.015|e=-25|u=s}}\n|-\n| [[Temperature]] (\u0398)\n| <math>T_{\\mathrm{QCD}} = \\frac{m_\\text{p} c^2}{k_\\text{B}}</math>\n| {{val|1.089|e=13|u=K}}\n|-\n|rowspan=3| [[Electric charge]] (Q)\n| <math>q_\\mathrm{QCD} = e</math> (original)\n| {{val|1.602|e=-19|u=C}}\n|-\n| <math>q_\\mathrm{QCD} = \\frac{e}{\\sqrt{4\\pi\\alpha}}</math> ([[Lorentz\u2013Heaviside units|L\u2013H]])\n| {{val|5.291|e=-19|u=C}}\n|-\n| <math>q_\\mathrm{QCD} = \\frac{e}{\\sqrt{\\alpha}}</math> ([[Gaussian units|G]])\n| {{val|1.876|e=-18|u=C}}\n|}\n\n:{{math|1=''c'' = ''m''{{sub|p}} = ''\u0127'' = ''k''{{sub|B}} = 1}} (in the original QCD units, {{math|''e''}} is also 1, if the QCD units are based on [[Lorentz\u2013Heaviside units]], then <math>\\epsilon_0</math> is 1, and if the QCD units are based on [[Gaussian units]], then <math>k_e = \\frac{1}{4 \\pi \\epsilon_0}</math> is 1)\n\nThe [[electron rest mass]] is replaced with that of the [[proton]]. ''Strong units'' are \"convenient for work in [[Quantum chromodynamics|QCD]] and nuclear physics, where quantum mechanics and relativity are omnipresent and the proton is an object of central interest\".<ref>Wilczek, Frank, 2007, \"[http://frankwilczek.com/Wilczek_Easy_Pieces/416_Fundamental_Constants.pdf Fundamental Constants,]\" ''Frank Wilczek'' web site.</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n===\"Natural units\" (particle physics and cosmology)===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" align=\"right\" style=\"margin-left: 1em; background-color: #ffffff\"\n! Unit\n! Metric value\n! Derivation\n|- align=\"left\"\n| 1 eV<sup>\u22121</sup> of length\n| {{val|1.97|e=-7|u=m}}\n| <math>=\\frac{\\hbar c}{1\\,\\text{eV}} </math>\n|-\n| 1 eV of mass\n| {{val|1.78|e=-36|u=kg}}\n| <math>= \\frac{1\\,\\text{eV}}{c^2}</math>\n|-\n| 1 eV<sup>\u22121</sup> of time\n| {{val|6.58|e=-16|u=s}}\n| <math>=\\frac{\\hbar}{1\\,\\text{eV}} </math>\n|-\n| 1 eV of temperature\n| {{val|1.16|e=4|u=K}}\n| <math>= \\frac{1\\,\\text{eV}}{k_\\text{B}}</math>\n|-\n| 1 unit of electric charge <br> ([[Lorentz\u2013Heaviside units|L\u2013H]])\n| {{val|5.29|e=-19|u=C}}\n| <math>=\\frac{e}{\\sqrt{4\\pi\\alpha}} </math>\n|-\n| 1 unit of electric charge <br> ([[Gaussian units|G]])\n| {{val|1.88|e=-18|u=C}}\n| <math>=\\frac{e}{\\sqrt{\\alpha}} </math>\n|}\n\nIn [[particle physics]] and [[cosmology]], the phrase \"natural units\" generally means:<ref>[http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/book/10.1002/9783527617357 ''Gauge field theories: an introduction with applications'', by Guidry, Appendix A]</ref><ref name=DT>[https://books.google.com/books?id=OF4TCxwpcN0C&pg=PA422 ''An introduction to cosmology and particle physics'', by Dom\u00ednguez-Tenreiro and Quir\u00f3s, p422]</ref>\n:{{math|1=''\u0127'' = ''c'' = ''k''{{sub|B}} = 1}}.\nwhere {{math|''\u0127''}} is the [[reduced Planck constant]], {{math|''c''}} is the [[speed of light]], and {{math|''k''<sub>B</sub>}} is the [[Boltzmann constant]].\n\nBoth Planck units and QCD units are this type of ''Natural units''. Like the other systems, the electromagnetism units can be based on either [[Lorentz\u2013Heaviside units]] or [[Gaussian units]]. The unit of charge is different in each.\n\nFinally, one more unit is needed to construct a usable system of units that includes energy and mass. Most commonly, [[electronvolt]] (eV) is used, despite the fact that this is not a \"natural\" unit in the sense discussed above \u2013 it is defined by a natural property, the [[elementary charge]], and the anthropogenic unit of [[electric potential]], the [[volt]]. (The [[SI prefix]]ed multiples of eV are used as well: keV, MeV, GeV, etc.)\n\nWith the addition of eV (or any other auxiliary unit with the proper dimension), any quantity can be expressed. For example, a distance of 1.0 [[centimeter|cm]] can be expressed in terms of eV, in natural units, as:<ref name=DT/>\n:{{math|1.0 cm {{=}} {{sfrac|1.0 cm|''\u0127c''}} \u2248 51000 eV{{sup|\u22121}}}}\n{{Clear}}\n\nIf the addition is 4{{pi}}''G'' (for Lorentz\u2013Heaviside units) or ''G'' (for Gaussian units) instead of eV, then the two kinds of ''Natural units'' are the same as the two kinds of Planck units.\n\n===Geometrized units===\n{{Main|Geometrized unit system}}\n\n:{{math|1=''c'' = ''G'' = 1}}\n\nThe geometrized unit system, used in [[general relativity]], is not a completely defined system. In this system, the base physical units are chosen so that the [[speed of light]] and the [[gravitational constant]] are set equal to unity. Other units may be treated however desired. Planck units and Stoney units are examples of geometrized unit systems.\n\n==See also==\n{{colbegin}}\n* [[Anthropic units]]\n* [[Dimensional analysis]]\n* [[Dimensionless physical constant]]\n* [[SI base unit]]\n* [[N-body units]]\n* [[Physical constant]]\n* [[Astronomical system of units]]\n*[[Planck units]]\n* [[Units of measurement]]\n{{colend}}\n\n== Notes and references ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat}}\n*[http://physics.nist.gov/cuu/ The NIST website] ([[NIST|National Institute of Standards and Technology]]) is a convenient source of data on the commonly recognized constants.\n*[http://www.ihst.ru/personal/tomilin/papers/tomil.pdf K.A. Tomilin: ''NATURAL SYSTEMS OF UNITS; To the Centenary Anniversary of the Planck System''] A comparative overview/tutorial of various systems of natural units having historical use.\n*[http://www.quantumfieldtheory.info Pedagogic Aides to Quantum Field Theory] Click on the link for Chap. 2 to find an extensive, simplified introduction to natural units.\n\n{{Systems of measurement}}\n{{Planck's natural units}}\n{{SI units}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Natural Units}}\n[[Category:Natural units| ]]\n[[Category:Metrology]]\n\n[[bs:Prirodne jedinice]]\n[[sr:\u041f\u0440\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043d\u0435 \u0458\u0435\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0435]]\n[[sh:Prirodne jedinice]]\n", "name_user": "Ahri6279", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSummary table", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natural_units"}
{"title_page": "Andy Johns", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Andy Johns\n| image               =\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = Johns at the mixing desk\n| background          = non_performing_personnel\n| birth_name          = Jeremy Andrew Johns\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| alias               = \n| birth_date          = {{birth date|1950|05|20|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Epsom]]\n| origin              = \n| death_date          = {{death date and age|2013|4|7|1950|05|20|df=y}}\n| death_place         = [[Los Angeles]]\n| genre               = [[Rock music|Rock]]\n| occupation          = [[Record producer]], [[Audio engineer|sound engineer]]\n| instrument          = \n| years_active        = 1960s\u20132013\n| label               = \n| associated_acts     = \n| website             = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n}}\n'''Jeremy Andrew \"Andy\" Johns''' (20 May 1950 \u2013 7 April 2013) was a [[British people|British]] [[Audio engineer|sound engineer]] and [[record producer]], who worked on several well-known rock albums, including [[the Rolling Stones]]' ''[[Exile on Main Street]]'' (1972), [[Television (band)|Television]]'s ''[[Marquee Moon]]'' (1977), and a series of albums by [[Led Zeppelin]] during the 1970s.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sisario|first=Ben|date=19 April 2013|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/04/20/arts/music/andy-johns-62-rolling-stones-and-led-zeppelin-engineer-dies.html?_r=0|title=Andy Johns, 62, Rolling Stones and Led Zeppelin Engineer, Dies|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=20 May 2014}}</ref> His sound is exemplified by [[Free (band)|Free]]'s album ''[[Highway (Free album)|Highway]]'', which he engineered and produced.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gibson.com/en-us/Lifestyle/Features/legendary-engineer-andy-johns |title=Legendary Engineer Andy Johns Looks Back at His Work with Free |publisher=Gibson.com |date=28 May 2008 |accessdate=8 April 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080530020618/http://www.gibson.com/en%2Dus/Lifestyle/Features/legendary%2Dengineer%2Dandy%2Djohns/ |archive-date=30 May 2008 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://bobbyowsinski.com/The_Mixing_Engineers_Handbook_-_Andy_Johns_Interview.html |title=The Mixing Engineer's Handbook \u2013 Andy Johns Interview |publisher=Bobbyowsinski.com |accessdate=8 April 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Dave Lewis|title=The Tight But Loose Files|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q2vLCdjw9kgC&pg=PA24|year=2003|publisher=Omnibus|isbn=978-1-84449-056-1|page=24}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nJohns, the younger brother of engineer [[Glyn Johns]], attended The [[King's School, Gloucester]], England in the mid to late 1960s.  He began his career as a tape operator in [[Olympic Studios]] in London.  While there he worked with [[Rod Stewart]], [[Jethro Tull (band)|Jethro Tull]] and [[Humble Pie]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Cashmere |first=Paul |date=8 April 2013 |title=Andy Johns, Led Zeppelin and Rolling Stones Engineer and Producer Dies |newspaper=Noise 11 |url=http://www.noise11.com/news/breaking-andy-johns-led-zeppelin-and-rolling-stones-engineer-and-producer-dies-20130408 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130409233039/http://www.noise11.com/news/breaking-andy-johns-led-zeppelin-and-rolling-stones-engineer-and-producer-dies-20130408 |archive-date=9 April 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> Before his nineteenth birthday, he was working as [[Eddie Kramer]]'s second engineer on recordings by [[Jimi Hendrix]] and many others. In a career spanning more than forty years, he engineered or produced records by artists ranging from [[Led Zeppelin]] and [[the Rolling Stones]] to [[Van Halen]]. Records he worked on sold in excess of 160 million copies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://guitarinternational.com/2011/04/23/andy-johns-interview-the-man-behind-the-sound-of-rock-n-roll/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110427081807/http://guitarinternational.com/2011/04/23/andy-johns-interview-the-man-behind-the-sound-of-rock-n-roll/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=27 April 2011 |title=Andy Johns Interview: The Man Behind the Sound of Rock n Roll : Guitar Interviews |publisher=Guitarinternational.com |accessdate=8 April 2013 }}</ref>\n\nJohns was the father of [[Hurt (band)|Hurt]]'s former drummer, Evan Johns, and of rock singer/guitarist [[Will Johns]], and uncle of producer [[Ethan Johns]] (son of Glyn Johns).\n\nJohns died on 7 April 2013, after a short stay in a Los Angeles hospital being treated for complications from a [[stomach ulcer]]. He was 62. Johns is survived by his wife Anet; sons Evan, Jesse and William; grandchildren Lennon, Everly, Charlie and Luca; sister Susan Johns; and brother Glyn Johns.<ref>{{cite web|title=LED ZEPPELIN, VAN HALEN PRODUCER ANDY JOHNS DIES |url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/led-zeppelin-van-halen-producer-andy-johns-dies#overlay-context=article/jay-z-sells-nets-losing-minor-owner-big-name |publisher=AP |accessdate=11 April 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131111103424/http://bigstory.ap.org/article/led-zeppelin-van-halen-producer-andy-johns-dies |archivedate=11 November 2013  }}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Albums produced===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n*''[[Ahead Rings Out]]'' \u2013 [[Blodwyn Pig]] (1969)\n*''[[As Safe as Yesterday Is]]'' \u2013 [[Humble Pie]] (1969)\n*''[[Town and Country (album)|Town and Country]]'' \u2013 [[Humble Pie]] (1969)\n*''Extraction'' \u2013 [[Gary Wright]] (1970)\n*''[[Highway (Free album)|Highway]]'' \u2013 [[Free (band)|Free]] (1970)\n*''[[Free Live!]]'' \u2013 Free (1971)\n*''[[Heartbreaker (Free album)|Heartbreaker]]'' \u2013 Free (1972)\n*''[[Bobby Whitlock (album)|Bobby Whitlock]]'' \u2013 [[Bobby Whitlock]] (1972)\n*''[[Why Dontcha]]'' \u2013 [[West, Bruce and Laing]] (1972)\n*''[[Out of the Storm (Jack Bruce album)|Out of the Storm]]'' \