*[http://www.platinumsamples.com/AndyJohns.html Platinum Samples \u2013 Andy Johns \"Classic Drums\"]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090403125554/http://www.shure.com/Artists/engineer_content_Andy_Johns Shure Artist Andy Johns]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090829065934/http://vintageking.com/site/files/archives.html Andy Johns \u2013 Recording Engineer/Producer October 1975]\n*{{discogs artist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Johns, Andy}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:2013 deaths]]\n[[Category:British audio engineers]]\n[[Category:British record producers]]\n[[Category:People educated at The King's School, Gloucester]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Andy Johns\n| image               =\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = Johns at the mixing desk\n| background          = non_performing_personnel\n| birth_name          = Jeremy Andrew Johns\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| alias               = \n| birth_date          = {{birth date|1950|05|20|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Epsom]]\n| origin              = \n| death_date          = {{death date and age|2013|4|7|1950|05|20|df=y}}\n| death_place         = [[Los Angeles]]\n| genre               = [[Rock music|Rock]]\n| occupation          = [[Record producer]], [[Audio engineer|sound engineer]]\n| instrument          = \n| years_active        = 1960s\u20132013\n| label               = \n| associated_acts     = \n| website             = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n}}\n'''Jeremy Andrew \"Andy\" Johns''' (20 May 1950 \u2013 7 April 2013) was a [[British people|British]] [[Audio engineer|sound engineer]] and [[record producer]], who worked on several well-known rock albums, including [[the Rolling Stones]]' ''[[Exile on Main Street]]'' (1972), [[Television (band)|Television]]'s ''[[Marquee Moon]]'' (1977), and a series of albums by [[Led Zeppelin]] during the 1970s.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sisario|first=Ben|date=19 April 2013|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/04/20/arts/music/andy-johns-62-rolling-stones-and-led-zeppelin-engineer-dies.html?_r=0|title=Andy Johns, 62, Rolling Stones and Led Zeppelin Engineer, Dies|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=20 May 2014}}</ref> His sound is exemplified by [[Free (band)|Free]]'s album ''[[Highway (Free album)|Highway]]'', which he engineered and produced.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gibson.com/en-us/Lifestyle/Features/legendary-engineer-andy-johns |title=Legendary Engineer Andy Johns Looks Back at His Work with Free |publisher=Gibson.com |date=28 May 2008 |accessdate=8 April 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080530020618/http://www.gibson.com/en%2Dus/Lifestyle/Features/legendary%2Dengineer%2Dandy%2Djohns/ |archive-date=30 May 2008 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://bobbyowsinski.com/The_Mixing_Engineers_Handbook_-_Andy_Johns_Interview.html |title=The Mixing Engineer's Handbook \u2013 Andy Johns Interview |publisher=Bobbyowsinski.com |accessdate=8 April 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Dave Lewis|title=The Tight But Loose Files|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q2vLCdjw9kgC&pg=PA24|year=2003|publisher=Omnibus|isbn=978-1-84449-056-1|page=24}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nJohns, the younger brother of engineer [[Glyn Johns]], attended The [[King's School, Gloucester]], England in the mid to late 1960s.  He began his career as a tape operator in [[Olympic Studios]] in London.  While there he worked with [[Rod Stewart]], [[Jethro Tull]] and [[Humble Pie]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Cashmere |first=Paul |date=8 April 2013 |title=Andy Johns, Led Zeppelin and Rolling Stones Engineer and Producer Dies |newspaper=Noise 11 |url=http://www.noise11.com/news/breaking-andy-johns-led-zeppelin-and-rolling-stones-engineer-and-producer-dies-20130408 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130409233039/http://www.noise11.com/news/breaking-andy-johns-led-zeppelin-and-rolling-stones-engineer-and-producer-dies-20130408 |archive-date=9 April 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> Before his nineteenth birthday, he was working as [[Eddie Kramer]]'s second engineer on recordings by [[Jimi Hendrix]] and many others. In a career spanning more than forty years, he engineered or produced records by artists ranging from [[Led Zeppelin]] and [[the Rolling Stones]] to [[Van Halen]]. Records he worked on sold in excess of 160 million copies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://guitarinternational.com/2011/04/23/andy-johns-interview-the-man-behind-the-sound-of-rock-n-roll/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110427081807/http://guitarinternational.com/2011/04/23/andy-johns-interview-the-man-behind-the-sound-of-rock-n-roll/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=27 April 2011 |title=Andy Johns Interview: The Man Behind the Sound of Rock n Roll : Guitar Interviews |publisher=Guitarinternational.com |accessdate=8 April 2013 }}</ref>\n\nJohns was the father of [[Hurt (band)|Hurt]]'s former drummer, Evan Johns, and of rock singer/guitarist [[Will Johns]], and uncle of producer [[Ethan Johns]] (son of Glyn Johns).\n\nJohns died on 7 April 2013, after a short stay in a Los Angeles hospital being treated for complications from a [[stomach ulcer]]. He was 62. Johns is survived by his wife Anet; sons Evan, Jesse and William; grandchildren Lennon, Everly, Charlie and Luca; sister Susan Johns; and brother Glyn Johns.<ref>{{cite web|title=LED ZEPPELIN, VAN HALEN PRODUCER ANDY JOHNS DIES |url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/led-zeppelin-van-halen-producer-andy-johns-dies#overlay-context=article/jay-z-sells-nets-losing-minor-owner-big-name |publisher=AP |accessdate=11 April 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131111103424/http://bigstory.ap.org/article/led-zeppelin-van-halen-producer-andy-johns-dies |archivedate=11 November 2013  }}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Albums produced===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n*''[[Ahead Rings Out]]'' \