]'' \u2013 [[Godsmack]] (2006)\n*''Radio Romeo'' \u2013 [[Radio Romeo]] (2007)\n*''[[Crossroads (Eric Clapton album)|Crossroads]]'' \u2013 [[Eric Clapton]]\n*''[[Eric Clapton (album)|Eric Clapton]]'' \u2013 [[Eric Clapton]]\n* [[Willie Basse]]  *\"Break Away\", [23][24] Rock's Cool Music Publishing, New Empire Media, Inc. (2010) Andy Johns Co-Producer, Engineer https://itun.es/us/Yu2xx{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} \n*''Ladies and Gentleman The Rolling Stones Movie'' \u2013 [[The Rolling Stones]]\n*''Double Four Time'' \u2013 The Swayback (2012)\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0424281}}\n*[http://www.platinumsamples.com/AndyJohns.html Platinum Samples \u2013 Andy Johns \"Classic Drums\"]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090403125554/http://www.shure.com/Artists/engineer_content_Andy_Johns Shure Artist Andy Johns]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090829065934/http://vintageking.com/site/files/archives.html Andy Johns \u2013 Recording Engineer/Producer October 1975]\n*{{discogs artist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Johns, Andy}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:2013 deaths]]\n[[Category:British audio engineers]]\n[[Category:British record producers]]\n[[Category:People educated at The King's School, Gloucester]]\n", "name_user": "GoingBatty", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 - Repaired 1 link to disambiguation page -(You can help)-Jethro Tull/WP:WCWproject (Missing end bold/italic)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andy_Johns"}
{"title_page": "David Threlfall", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                  = David Threlfall\n| image                 =\n| birth_date            = {{Birth date and age|1957|10|12|df=y}}\n| birth_place           = [[Crumpsall]], [[Manchester]], [[Lancashire]], England\n| death_date  4th of april 2020         = \n| death_place [[Camden]] [[Kentish town]]                    = \n| birth_name             = David J. Threlfall<ref> ''England & Wales, Civil Registration Birth Index, 1916-2007''</ref><ref>''England & Wales, Civil Registration Marriage Index, 1916-2005''</ref>\n| occupation            = [[Actor]], [[television director|director]]\n| years_active          = 1977\u20132020\n| spouse                = {{marriage|[[Brana Bajic]]|1995}}<ref>{{cite news|author=Gerard Gilbert |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/david-threlfall-interview-the-actor-takes-a-forensic-approach-in-code-of-a-killer-as-he-leaves-10132763.html |title=David Threlfall interview: The actor takes a forensic approach in Code of a Killer as he leaves Shameless's Frank Gallagher behind |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |date=2015-03-28 |accessdate=2017-07-08}}</ref>\n| children = 2\n| website               = \n}}\n\n'''David Threlfall''' (born 12 October 1957) is an English stage, film and television [[actor]] and [[television director|director]]. He is best known for playing [[Frank Gallagher (Shameless)|Frank Gallagher]] in [[Channel 4]]'s series ''[[Shameless (UK TV series)|Shameless]]''. He has also directed several episodes of the show. In April 2014, he portrayed comedian [[Tommy Cooper]] in a television film entitled ''[[Tommy Cooper: Not Like That, Like This]]''. In 2014, he starred alongside [[Jude Law]] in the thriller ''[[Black Sea (film)|Black Sea]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nThe son of a [[plumber]], Tommy Threlfall and his wife, Joyce Foulds, David was born in [[Crumpsall]], [[Manchester]], [[Lancashire]]. The family lived in Blackley then moved to the Bradford area of Manchester and then Burnage when he was 8/9.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/david-threlfall-frank-in-more-than-one-sense-431004.html|title=David Threlfall: Frank, in more than one sense|last=Jury |first=Louise|work=[[The Independent]] |location=UK  |date=6 January 2007 |accessdate=7 June 2011}}</ref> His introduction to drama came from school and two [[English language|English]] teachers, at Wilbraham High School, where he was a contemporary of the younger [[Lorraine Ashbourne]]. Encouragement from those teachers led to his playing the male lead in a four-performance school production of [[Ann Jellicoe]]'s ''Rising Generation'' in 1971. December that year saw him playing John Proctor in a school production of ''[[The Crucible]]'' and then to his getting involved with [[Manchester Youth Theatre]].\n\nHe studied at Art college in [[Sheffield]] (now [[Sheffield Hallam University]]), but only stayed for a year. A few months of labouring and thinking followed. Then, having consulted a magazine in a [[public library]] which listed drama colleges, Threlfall successfully applied to Manchester Polytechnic School of Drama. By graduation, he had an audition with [[Mike Leigh]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/life/features/david-threlfall-i-drive-directors-nuts-im-a-bit-of-a-handful-31113582.html|title=David Threlfall: I drive directors nuts, I'm a bit of a handful'|work=BelfastTelegraph.co.uk|access-date=2017-12-05|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nThrelfall has been a keen supporter of [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] since childhood and is the voice over for the film played before every home game .<ref>[http://fourfourtwo.com/interviews/celebrityfans/51/article.aspx Celebrity fans: David Threlfall], ''FourFourTwo.com''</ref>\n\n==Career==\nThrelfall graduated from the [[Manchester Polytechnic School of Theatre]]. He has notched up a wide range of film and television credits since his 1977 acting debut in \"The Kiss of Death\" (Mike Leigh). Was in  the original ''[[Play for Today]]'' version of the film ''[[Scum (film)|Scum]]'' as the eloquent Archer.<ref name=\"Ind070107\">Pryor, Cathy, [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/david-threlfall-being-frank-and-shameless-431142.html David Threlfall: Being Frank and Shameless], ''Independent.co.uk'', 7 January 2007</ref> Television appearances include Trevor in [[Mike Leigh]]'s 1977 made-for-TV film ''[[Kiss of Death (1977 film)|Kiss of Death]]'', Leslie Titmuss in ''[[Paradise Postponed]]'', Edgar in the [[Granada Television]] production of ''[[King Lear (1983 TV programme)|King Lear]]'' (1983) opposite [[Laurence Olivier]] in the title role. He also had regular roles in the [[situation comedy|situation comedies]] ''[[Nightingales (UK TV series)|Nightingales]]'' and ''[[Men of the World]]'', and guest appearances in dramas such as ''[[Cutting It]]'', ''[[The Knock]]'', ''[[CI5: The New Professionals]]'' and ''[[Spooks (TV series)|Spooks]]''. He played [[Charles, Prince of Wales|Prince Charles]] in ''Diana: Her True Story'' (1993) and his father [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|Prince Philip]] in ''[[The Queen's Sister]]'' (2005). Threlfall played the central character of [[Frank Gallagher (Shameless)|Frank Gallagher]] in [[Paul Abbott]]'s ''[[Shameless (UK TV series)|Shameless]]'', shown on [[Channel 4]] for 11 series between 2004 and 2013.\n\nHe also played the role of [[Friedrich Kritzinger]] in the BBC/HBO drama ''[[Conspiracy (2001 film)|Conspiracy]]'', a dramatisation of the infamous [[Wannsee Conference]]. In 2006, he played the domineering husband of wartime diarist [[Nella Last]], in the TV drama ''[[Housewife, 49]]''. Film credits include [[John le Carr\u00e9]]'s ''[[The Russia House (film)|The Russia House]]'', ''[[Patriot Games (film)|Patriot Games]]'', ''[[Master and Commander: The Far Side of the World]]'', ''[[Elizabeth: The Golden Age]]'', alongside [[Cate Blanchett]], and ''[[Nowhere Boy]]'' in which he took the part of [[John Lennon]]'s [[George Toogood Smith|Uncle George]].\n\nHe also had a small role in the 2006 film ''[[Alien Autopsy (film)|Alien Autopsy]]'' and played the character Martin Blower in the 2007 film ''[[Hot Fuzz]]'', acting alongside [[Simon Pegg]] and [[Nick Frost]]. He starred in an episode of ''The Whistle Blowers''. He starred as the lead role in the fifth episode of the BBC docu-drama series ''[[Ancient Rome: The Rise and Fall of an Empire]]'' as the Emperor [[Constantine I]].\n\nThrelfall voiced the part of Iago in ''Othello'' for the Arcangel audio production of same. He also voiced the detective Paolo Baldi in [[BBC Radio 4]]'s ''[[Baldi (radio)|Baldi]]''.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/northernireland/drama/radio/baldi4.shtml BALDI SERIES 4], ''BBC.co.uk''</ref> He also read [[Joseph Conrad]]'s ''[[Heart of Darkness]]'' for a radio adaptation. In 1980, he played Smike in the eight-hour stage version of ''[[The Life and Adventures of Nicholas Nickleby (play)|The Life and Adventures of Nicholas Nickleby]]'' for the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]] in both [[London]] and [[New York City|New York]].\n\nOther notable stage performances include ''[[Riddley Walker]]'', ''[[Oedipus]]'', ''[[Macbeth]], Your Home In The West'' and ''[[Peer Gynt]]'' at the [[Royal Exchange Theatre]], [[Manchester]], Bolingbroke in ''[[Richard II (play)|Richard II]]'' and Orgon in ''[[Tartuffe]]'' at the [[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre]] in London. Threlfall played Jack in ''When the Whales Came'' (1989), opposite [[Paul Scofield]] and [[Helen Mirren]]. In 2010, he appeared as a guest on ''[[Have I Got News for You]]''.\n\nIn 2013, he played retired London detective Len Harper in the short murder mystery BBC series ''[[What Remains (TV series)|What Remains]]'' alongside [[Russell Tovey]] and [[Amber Rose Revah]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/mediapacks/whatremains/amber-rose-revah.html|title=BBC - Q&A with Amber Rose Revah - Media Centre|website=www.bbc.co.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-03-29}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, he appeared as the lead in ''Don Quixote'', at the Swan Theatre, Stratford for the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]]. The play was revived in 2018 at the Garrick Theatre in London.\n\n==Awards and honours==\nThrelfall was awarded an Honorary Doctorate from Manchester Metropolitan University on 15 July 2013. An Honorary Doctorate from Sheffield Hallam University in 2014. He has a SWET (Olivier) Award, a TONY and EMMY Nomination, The Clarence Derwent Award, 5 RTS Awards and a BAFTA for Housewife49 with Victoria Wood.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.mmu.ac.uk/about/honorary-graduates/honorands-2013/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160223024811/http://www2.mmu.ac.uk/about/honorary-graduates/honorands-2013/ |archivedate=23 February 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nThrelfall has been married to [[Bosnians|Bosnian]] actress [[Brana Bajic]] since 1991.<ref name=\"St060504\">Elkin, Susan, [http://www.thestage.co.uk/features/feature.php/2012 Art of the shapeshifter \u2014 David Threlfall], ''TheStage.co.uk'', 6 May 2004</ref> They met in 1990, whilst working on ''The Count of Monte Cristo'' at the Royal Exchange Theatre in Manchester.<ref name=\"St060504\"/>\n\nThrelfall has said that despite his ''Shameless'' character being a chain smoker, in real life he is a non-smoker who has a dislike for nicotine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/celebs/news/2007/01/05/we-re-so-shameless-115875-18393942/ |title=Celebrity news: gossip, pictures & video |website=Mirror.co.uk |date=2017-05-27 |accessdate=2017-07-08}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[Patriot Games (film)|Patriot Games]]''\n| Inspector Highland\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''[[Master and Commander: The Far Side of the World]]''\n| Preserved Killick\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''Alien Autopsy''\n| Jeffrey (Film restorer)\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2007\n| ''[[Hot Fuzz]]'' \n| Some Feen\n|-\n| ''[[Elizabeth: The Golden Age]]''\n| John Dee\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Nowhere Boy]]''\n| George Smith\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Black Sea (film)|Black Sea]]'' \n| Peters\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n|-\n| 1977\n| ''[[Scum (television play)|Scum]]''\n| Archer\n|-\n| 1982\n| ''[[The Life and Adventures of Nicholas Nickleby (1982 film)|The Life and Adventures of Nicholas Nickleby]]''\n| Smike\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[Paradise Postponed]]'' \n| Leslie Titmuss\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''[[Frederick Forsyth Presents#A Casualty of War|Frederick Forsyth Presents: A Casualty of War]]''\n| Tom Rowse\n|-\n| 1990\u20131993\n| ''[[Nightingales (UK TV series)|Nightingales]]'' \n| \"Ding Dong\" Bell\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1991\n| ''Titmuss Regained'' \n| Leslie Titmuss\n|-\n| ''[[A Murder of Quality (film)|A Murder of Quality]]''\n| Stanley Rode\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[Catherine Cookson's A Dinner of Herbs (2000 film)|Catherine Cookson's A Dinner of Herbs]]'' \n| [[Hal Royston]]\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[Conspiracy (2001 film)|Conspiracy]]'' \n| [[Friedrich Wilhelm Kritzinger|Dr Friedrich Wilhelm Kritzinger]]\n|-\n| 2004\u20132013\n| ''[[Shameless (UK TV series)|Shameless]]'' \n| [[Frank Gallagher (Shameless)|Frank trampagher]]\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Housewife, 49]]''\n| William Last\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[What Remains (TV series)|What Remains]]'' \n| DI Len Harper\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Tommy Cooper: Not Like That, Like This]]'' \n| [[Tommy Cooper]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2015\n| ''[[The Ark (TV series)|The Ark]]'' \n| Noah\n|-\n| ''[[Code of a Killer]]'' \n| Detective David Baker\n|-\n| 2015/2016\n| ''[[Midwinter of the Spirit]]''<ref>{{cite web|last=Fletcher |first=Harry |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a640144/david-threlfall-anna-maxwell-martin-for-itvs-midwinter-of-the-spirit.html#~p9USQR06N4YMsW |title=David Threlfall, Anna Maxwell-Martin for ITV's Midwinter of the Spirit |website=Digitalspy.co.uk |date=2015-04-07 |accessdate=2017-07-08}}</ref>\n| Rev Huw Owen\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Ripper Street]]'' \n| Abel Croker\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Troy: Fall of a City]]'' \n| [[Priam]]\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Bing (TV series)|Bing]]''\n| Flop (voice)\n|}\n\n==Theatre<ref>[[Braham Murray|Murray, Braham]] (2007). ''The Worst It Can Be Is a Disaster''. London: Methuen Drama. {{ISBN|978-0-7136-8490-2}}.</ref><ref>The Royal Exchange Theatre Company Words & Pictures 1976-1998, 1998, {{ISBN|0-9512017-1-9}}</ref>==\n\n* Blackie, ''The Sons of Light'' by [[David Rudkin]] for the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]] at [[The Other Place (theatre)|The Other Place]], [[Stratford-upon-Avon]] (1977)\n* Jake, ''A&R'' by [[Pete Atkin]] for the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]] at the [[Donmar Warehouse|Warehouse Theatre]], London (1978)\n* Fitz, ''Savage Amusement'' by [[Peter Flannery]] for the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]] at the [[Donmar Warehouse|Warehouse Theatre]], London (1978)\n* Mike, ''Shout Across The River'' by [[Stephen Poliakoff]] for the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]] at the [[Donmar Warehouse|Warehouse Theatre]], London (1978)\n* [[Mark Antony]], ''[[Julius Caesar (play)|Julius Caesar]]'' at the [[Royal Shakespeare Theatre]], Stratford-upon-Avon (1979)\n* Slender, ''[[The Merry Wives of Windsor]]'' at the [[Royal Shakespeare Theatre]], Stratford-upon-Avon (1979)\n* Viktor, ''[[The Suicide (play)|The Suicide]]'' by [[Nikolai Erdman]] for the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]] at [[The Other Place (theatre)|The Other Place]], Stratford-upon-Avon (1979)\n* Smike, ''[[The Life and Adventures of Nicholas Nickleby (play)|The Life and Adventures of Nicholas Nickleby]]'' adapted by [[David Edgar (playwright)|David Edgar]] for the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]] at the [[Aldwych Theatre]], London and then at the [[Plymouth Theatre]], New York (1980)\n* Bolingbroke, ''[[Richard II]]'' at the [[Royal National Theatre]], London (1985)\n* Riddley Walker, ''[[Riddley Walker]]'' by [[Russell Hoban]] at the [[Royal Exchange, Manchester]] (1986)\n* ''[[Hamlet]]'' for the [[Oxford Playhouse]] at the [[Edinburgh Festival]] (1986)\n*Oedipus, [[Oedipus]] by [[Sophocles]] at the [[Royal Exchange, Manchester]] (1987)\n* ''The Traveller'' by Jean Claude Van Itallie at the [[Leicester Haymarket Theatre|Haymarket Theatre]], [[Leicester]] and then the [[Almeida Theatre|Almeida]] (1987)\n* Macbeth, ''[[Macbeth]]'' at the [[Royal Exchange, Manchester]] (1988)\n* ''[[Bussy D'Ambois]]'' by [[George Chapman]] at the [[Old Vic]] (1988)\n* Ian, ''Over a Barrel'' by Stephen Bill, [[Watford Palace Theatre|Palace Theatre]], [[Watford]] (1989)\n* Gregers Werle, ''[[The Wild Duck]]'' by [[Henrik Ibsen]] at the [[Phoenix Theatre (London)|Phoenix Theatre]], London (1990)\n* Micky, ''Your Home in the West'' by Rod Wooden at the [[Royal Exchange, Manchester]] (1991)\n* The Count, ''[[The Count of Monte Cristo]]'' at the [[Royal Exchange, Manchester]] (1994)\n* Lovborg, ''[[Hedda Gabler]]'' by [[Henrik Ibsen]] at the [[Chichester Festival Theatre]] (1996)\n* Norman Nestor, ''Odysseus Thump'' by Richard Hope at the [[West Yorkshire Playhouse]], [[Leeds]] (1997)\n* Garry Essendine, ''[[Present Laughter]]'' by [[No\u00ebl Coward]] at the [[Royal Exchange, Manchester]] (1998)\n* [[Peer Gynt]] by ''[[Henrik Ibsen]]'' at the [[Royal Exchange, Manchester]] (1999)\n* Orgon, ''[[Tartuffe]]'' by [[Moliere]] at the [[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre]], London (2002)\n* Robert ''[[Blue/Orange]]'' by [[Joe Penhall]] at the [[Duchess Theatre]], London (2001)\n* ''[[Skellig]]'' by [[David Almond]] at the [[Young Vic]], London (2003)\n* Michael, ''[[Someone Who'll Watch Over Me]]'' by [[Frank McGuiness]] at the [[Ambassadors Theatre (London)|Ambassadors Theatre]], London (2005)\n* Don Quixote, ''[[Don Quixote]]'' adapted by [[James Fenton]] from the novel by [[Miguel de Cervantes]] at the [[Swan Theatre, Stratford-upon-Avon]], 2016.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0861915}}\n\n{{OlivierAward PlayActor SupportingPerformance 1976\u20132000}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Threlfall, David}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Manchester]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Manchester Metropolitan University]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\n[[Category:Actors at the Royal Exchange, Manchester]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Royal Shakespeare Company members]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                  = David Threlfall\n| image                 =\n| birth_date            = {{Birth date and age|1953|10|12|df=y}}\n| birth_place           = [[Crumpsall]], [[Manchester]], [[Lancashire]], England\n| death_date            = \n| death_place           = \n| birth_name             = David J. Threlfall<ref> ''England & Wales, Civil Registration Birth Index, 1916-2007''</ref><ref>''England & Wales, Civil Registration Marriage Index, 1916-2005''</ref>\n| occupation            = [[Actor]], [[television director|director]]\n| years_active          = 1977\u2013present\n| spouse                = {{marriage|[[Brana Bajic]]|1995}}<ref>{{cite news|author=Gerard Gilbert |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/david-threlfall-interview-the-actor-takes-a-forensic-approach-in-code-of-a-killer-as-he-leaves-10132763.html |title=David Threlfall interview: The actor takes a forensic approach in Code of a Killer as he leaves Shameless's Frank Gallagher behind |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |date=2015-03-28 |accessdate=2017-07-08}}</ref>\n| children = 2\n| website               = \n}}\n\n'''David Threlfall''' (born 12 October 1953) is an English stage, film and television [[actor]] and [[television director|director]]. He is best known for playing [[Frank Gallagher (Shameless)|Frank Gallagher]] in [[Channel 4]]'s series ''[[Shameless (UK TV series)|Shameless]]''. He has also directed several episodes of the show. In April 2014, he portrayed comedian [[Tommy Cooper]] in a television film entitled ''[[Tommy Cooper: Not Like That, Like This]]''. In 2014, he starred alongside [[Jude Law]] in the thriller ''[[Black Sea (film)|Black Sea]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nThe son of a [[plumber]], Tommy Threlfall and his wife, Joyce Foulds, David was born in [[Crumpsall]], [[Manchester]], [[Lancashire]]. The family lived in Blackley then moved to the Bradford area of Manchester and then Burnage when he was 8/9.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/david-threlfall-frank-in-more-than-one-sense-431004.html|title=David Threlfall: Frank, in more than one sense|last=Jury |first=Louise|work=[[The Independent]] |location=UK  |date=6 January 2007 |accessdate=7 June 2011}}</ref> His introduction to drama came from school and two [[English language|English]] teachers, at Wilbraham High School, where he was a contemporary of the younger [[Lorraine Ashbourne]]. Encouragement from those teachers led to his playing the male lead in a four-performance school production of [[Ann Jellicoe]]'s ''Rising Generation'' in 1971. December that year saw him playing John Proctor in a school production of ''[[The Crucible]]'' and then to his getting involved with [[Manchester Youth Theatre]].\n\nHe studied at Art college in [[Sheffield]] (now [[Sheffield Hallam University]]), but only stayed for a year. A few months of labouring and thinking followed. Then, having consulted a magazine in a [[public library]] which listed drama colleges, Threlfall successfully applied to Manchester Polytechnic School of Drama. By graduation, he had an audition with [[Mike Leigh]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/life/features/david-threlfall-i-drive-directors-nuts-im-a-bit-of-a-handful-31113582.html|title=David Threlfall: I drive directors nuts, I'm a bit of a handful'|work=BelfastTelegraph.co.uk|access-date=2017-12-05|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nThrelfall has been a keen supporter of [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] since childhood and is the voice over for the film played before every home game .<ref>[http://fourfourtwo.com/interviews/celebrityfans/51/article.aspx Celebrity fans: David Threlfall], ''FourFourTwo.com''</ref>\n\n==Career==\nThrelfall graduated from the [[Manchester Polytechnic School of Theatre]]. He has notched up a wide range of film and television credits since his 1977 acting debut in \"The Kiss of Death\" (Mike Leigh). Was in  the original ''[[Play for Today]]'' version of the film ''[[Scum (film)|Scum]]'' as the eloquent Archer.<ref name=\"Ind070107\">Pryor, Cathy, [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/david-threlfall-being-frank-and-shameless-431142.html David Threlfall: Being Frank and Shameless], ''Independent.co.uk'', 7 January 2007</ref> Television appearances include Trevor in [[Mike Leigh]]'s 1977 made-for-TV film ''[[Kiss of Death (1977 film)|Kiss of Death]]'', Leslie Titmuss in ''[[Paradise Postponed]]'', Edgar in the [[Granada Television]] production of ''[[King Lear (1983 TV programme)|King Lear]]'' (1983) opposite [[Laurence Olivier]] in the title role. He also had regular roles in the [[situation comedy|situation comedies]] ''[[Nightingales (UK TV series)|Nightingales]]'' and ''[[Men of the World]]'', and guest appearances in dramas such as ''[[Cutting It]]'', ''[[The Knock]]'', ''[[CI5: The New Professionals]]'' and ''[[Spooks (TV series)|Spooks]]''. He played [[Charles, Prince of Wales|Prince Charles]] in ''Diana: Her True Story'' (1993) and his father [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|Prince Philip]] in ''[[The Queen's Sister]]'' (2005). Threlfall played the central character of [[Frank Gallagher (Shameless)|Frank Gallagher]] in [[Paul Abbott]]'s ''[[Shameless (UK TV series)|Shameless]]'', shown on [[Channel 4]] for 11 series between 2004 and 2013.\n\nHe also played the role of [[Friedrich Kritzinger]] in the BBC/HBO drama ''[[Conspiracy (2001 film)|Conspiracy]]'', a dramatisation of the infamous [[Wannsee Conference]]. In 2006, he played the domineering husband of wartime diarist [[Nella Last]], in the TV drama ''[[Housewife, 49]]''. Film credits include [[John le Carr\u00e9]]'s ''[[The Russia House (film)|The Russia House]]'', ''[[Patriot Games (film)|Patriot Games]]'', ''[[Master and Commander: The Far Side of the World]]'', ''[[Elizabeth: The Golden Age]]'', alongside [[Cate Blanchett]], and ''[[Nowhere Boy]]'' in which he took the part of [[John Lennon]]'s [[George Toogood Smith|Uncle George]].\n\nHe also had a small role in the 2006 film ''[[Alien Autopsy (film)|Alien Autopsy]]'' and played the character Martin Blower in the 2007 film ''[[Hot Fuzz]]'', acting alongside [[Simon Pegg]] and [[Nick Frost]]. He starred in an episode of ''The Whistle Blowers''. He starred as the lead role in the fifth episode of the BBC docu-drama series ''[[Ancient Rome: The Rise and Fall of an Empire]]'' as the Emperor [[Constantine I]].\n\nThrelfall voiced the part of Iago in ''Othello'' for the Arcangel audio production of same. He also voiced the detective Paolo Baldi in [[BBC Radio 4]]'s ''[[Baldi (radio)|Baldi]]''.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/northernireland/drama/radio/baldi4.shtml BALDI SERIES 4], ''BBC.co.uk''</ref> He also read [[Joseph Conrad]]'s ''[[Heart of Darkness]]'' for a radio adaptation. In 1980, he played Smike in the eight-hour stage version of ''[[The Life and Adventures of Nicholas Nickleby (play)|The Life and Adventures of Nicholas Nickleby]]'' for the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]] in both [[London]] and [[New York City|New York]].\n\nOther notable stage performances include ''[[Riddley Walker]]'', ''[[Oedipus]]'', ''[[Macbeth]], Your Home In The West'' and ''[[Peer Gynt]]'' at the [[Royal Exchange Theatre]], [[Manchester]], Bolingbroke in ''[[Richard II (play)|Richard II]]'' and Orgon in ''[[Tartuffe]]'' at the [[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre]] in London. Threlfall played Jack in ''When the Whales Came'' (1989), opposite [[Paul Scofield]] and [[Helen Mirren]]. In 2010, he appeared as a guest on ''[[Have I Got News for You]]''.\n\nIn 2013, he played retired London detective Len Harper in the short murder mystery BBC series ''[[What Remains (TV series)|What Remains]]'' alongside [[Russell Tovey]] and [[Amber Rose Revah]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/mediapacks/whatremains/amber-rose-revah.html|title=BBC - Q&A with Amber Rose Revah - Media Centre|website=www.bbc.co.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-03-29}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, he appeared as the lead in ''Don Quixote'', at the Swan Theatre, Stratford for the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]]. The play was revived in 2018 at the Garrick Theatre in London.\n\n==Awards and honours==\nThrelfall was awarded an Honorary Doctorate from Manchester Metropolitan University on 15 July 2013. An Honorary Doctorate from Sheffield Hallam University in 2014. He has a SWET (Olivier) Award, a TONY and EMMY Nomination, The Clarence Derwent Award, 5 RTS Awards and a BAFTA for Housewife49 with Victoria Wood.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.mmu.ac.uk/about/honorary-graduates/honorands-2013/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160223024811/http://www2.mmu.ac.uk/about/honorary-graduates/honorands-2013/ |archivedate=23 February 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nThrelfall has been married to [[Bosnians|Bosnian]] actress [[Brana Bajic]] since 1995.<ref name=\"St060504\">Elkin, Susan, [http://www.thestage.co.uk/features/feature.php/2012 Art of the shapeshifter \u2014 David Threlfall], ''TheStage.co.uk'', 6 May 2004</ref> They met in 1994, whilst working on ''The Count of Monte Cristo'' at the Royal Exchange Theatre in Manchester.<ref name=\"St060504\"/>\n\nThrelfall has said that despite his ''Shameless'' character being a chain smoker, in real life he is a non-smoker who has a dislike for nicotine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/celebs/news/2007/01/05/we-re-so-shameless-115875-18393942/ |title=Celebrity news: gossip, pictures & video |website=Mirror.co.uk |date=2017-05-27 |accessdate=2017-07-08}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[Patriot Games (film)|Patriot Games]]''\n| Inspector Highland\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''[[Master and Commander: The Far Side of the World]]''\n| Preserved Killick\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''Alien Autopsy''\n| Jeffrey (Film restorer)\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2007\n| ''[[Hot Fuzz]]'' \n| Martin Blower\n|-\n| ''[[Elizabeth: The Golden Age]]''\n| John Dee\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Nowhere Boy]]''\n| George Smith\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Black Sea (film)|Black Sea]]'' \n| Peters\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n|-\n| 1977\n| ''[[Scum (television play)|Scum]]''\n| Archer\n|-\n| 1982\n| ''[[The Life and Adventures of Nicholas Nickleby (1982 film)|The Life and Adventures of Nicholas Nickleby]]''\n| Smike\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[Paradise Postponed]]'' \n| Leslie Titmuss\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''[[Frederick Forsyth Presents#A Casualty of War|Frederick Forsyth Presents: A Casualty of War]]''\n| Tom Rowse\n|-\n| 1990\u20131993\n| ''[[Nightingales (UK TV series)|Nightingales]]'' \n| \"Ding Dong\" Bell\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1991\n| ''Titmuss Regained'' \n| Leslie Titmuss\n|-\n| ''[[A Murder of Quality (film)|A Murder of Quality]]''\n| Stanley Rode\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[Catherine Cookson's A Dinner of Herbs (2000 film)|Catherine Cookson's A Dinner of Herbs]]'' \n| [[Hal Royston]]\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[Conspiracy (2001 film)|Conspiracy]]'' \n| [[Friedrich Wilhelm Kritzinger|Dr Friedrich Wilhelm Kritzinger]]\n|-\n| 2004\u20132013\n| ''[[Shameless (UK TV series)|Shameless]]'' \n| [[Frank Gallagher (Shameless)|Frank Gallagher]]\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Housewife, 49]]''\n| William Last\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[What Remains (TV series)|What Remains]]'' \n| DI Len Harper\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Tommy Cooper: Not Like That, Like This]]'' \n| [[Tommy Cooper]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2015\n| ''[[The Ark (TV series)|The Ark]]'' \n| Noah\n|-\n| ''[[Code of a Killer]]'' \n| Detective David Baker\n|-\n| 2015/2016\n| ''[[Midwinter of the Spirit]]''<ref>{{cite web|last=Fletcher |first=Harry |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a640144/david-threlfall-anna-maxwell-martin-for-itvs-midwinter-of-the-spirit.html#~p9USQR06N4YMsW |title=David Threlfall, Anna Maxwell-Martin for ITV's Midwinter of the Spirit |website=Digitalspy.co.uk |date=2015-04-07 |accessdate=2017-07-08}}</ref>\n| Rev Huw Owen\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Ripper Street]]'' \n| Abel Croker\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Troy: Fall of a City]]'' \n| [[Priam]]\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Bing (TV series)|Bing]]''\n| Flop (voice)\n|}\n\n==Theatre<ref>[[Braham Murray|Murray, Braham]] (2007). ''The Worst It Can Be Is a Disaster''. London: Methuen Drama. {{ISBN|978-0-7136-8490-2}}.</ref><ref>The Royal Exchange Theatre Company Words & Pictures 1976-1998, 1998, {{ISBN|0-9512017-1-9}}</ref>==\n\n* Blackie, ''The Sons of Light'' by [[David Rudkin]] for the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]] at [[The Other Place (theatre)|The Other Place]], [[Stratford-upon-Avon]] (1977)\n* Jake, ''A&R'' by [[Pete Atkin]] for the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]] at the [[Donmar Warehouse|Warehouse Theatre]], London (1978)\n* Fitz, ''Savage Amusement'' by [[Peter Flannery]] for the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]] at the [[Donmar Warehouse|Warehouse Theatre]], London (1978)\n* Mike, ''Shout Across The River'' by [[Stephen Poliakoff]] for the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]] at the [[Donmar Warehouse|Warehouse Theatre]], London (1978)\n* [[Mark Antony]], ''[[Julius Caesar (play)|Julius Caesar]]'' at the [[Royal Shakespeare Theatre]], Stratford-upon-Avon (1979)\n* Slender, ''[[The Merry Wives of Windsor]]'' at the [[Royal Shakespeare Theatre]], Stratford-upon-Avon (1979)\n* Viktor, ''[[The Suicide (play)|The Suicide]]'' by [[Nikolai Erdman]] for the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]] at [[The Other Place (theatre)|The Other Place]], Stratford-upon-Avon (1979)\n* Smike, ''[[The Life and Adventures of Nicholas Nickleby (play)|The Life and Adventures of Nicholas Nickleby]]'' adapted by [[David Edgar (playwright)|David Edgar]] for the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]] at the [[Aldwych Theatre]], London and then at the [[Plymouth Theatre]], New York (1980)\n* Bolingbroke, ''[[Richard II]]'' at the [[Royal National Theatre]], London (1985)\n* Riddley Walker, ''[[Riddley Walker]]'' by [[Russell Hoban]] at the [[Royal Exchange, Manchester]] (1986)\n* ''[[Hamlet]]'' for the [[Oxford Playhouse]] at the [[Edinburgh Festival]] (1986)\n*Oedipus, [[Oedipus]] by [[Sophocles]] at the [[Royal Exchange, Manchester]] (1987)\n* ''The Traveller'' by Jean Claude Van Itallie at the [[Leicester Haymarket Theatre|Haymarket Theatre]], [[Leicester]] and then the [[Almeida Theatre|Almeida]] (1987)\n* Macbeth, ''[[Macbeth]]'' at the [[Royal Exchange, Manchester]] (1988)\n* ''[[Bussy D'Ambois]]'' by [[George Chapman]] at the [[Old Vic]] (1988)\n* Ian, ''Over a Barrel'' by Stephen Bill, [[Watford Palace Theatre|Palace Theatre]], [[Watford]] (1989)\n* Gregers Werle, ''[[The Wild Duck]]'' by [[Henrik Ibsen]] at the [[Phoenix Theatre (London)|Phoenix Theatre]], London (1990)\n* Micky, ''Your Home in the West'' by Rod Wooden at the [[Royal Exchange, Manchester]] (1991)\n* The Count, ''[[The Count of Monte Cristo]]'' at the [[Royal Exchange, Manchester]] (1994)\n* Lovborg, ''[[Hedda Gabler]]'' by [[Henrik Ibsen]] at the [[Chichester Festival Theatre]] (1996)\n* Norman Nestor, ''Odysseus Thump'' by Richard Hope at the [[West Yorkshire Playhouse]], [[Leeds]] (1997)\n* Garry Essendine, ''[[Present Laughter]]'' by [[No\u00ebl Coward]] at the [[Royal Exchange, Manchester]] (1998)\n* [[Peer Gynt]] by ''[[Henrik Ibsen]]'' at the [[Royal Exchange, Manchester]] (1999)\n* Orgon, ''[[Tartuffe]]'' by [[Moliere]] at the [[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre]], London (2002)\n* Robert ''[[Blue/Orange]]'' by [[Joe Penhall]] at the [[Duchess Theatre]], London (2001)\n* ''[[Skellig]]'' by [[David Almond]] at the [[Young Vic]], London (2003)\n* Michael, ''[[Someone Who'll Watch Over Me]]'' by [[Frank McGuiness]] at the [[Ambassadors Theatre (London)|Ambassadors Theatre]], London (2005)\n* Don Quixote, ''[[Don Quixote]]'' adapted by [[James Fenton]] from the novel by [[Miguel de Cervantes]] at the [[Swan Theatre, Stratford-upon-Avon]], 2016.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0861915}}\n\n{{OlivierAward PlayActor SupportingPerformance 1976\u20132000}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Threlfall, David}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Manchester]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Manchester Metropolitan University]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\n[[Category:Actors at the Royal Exchange, Manchester]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Royal Shakespeare Company members]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:c7d:b94e:f400:659e:ea8f:2a7e:cfb3", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eFilm)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Threlfall"}
{"title_page": "I'm on Fire", "text_new": "{{other uses}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = I'm on Fire\n| cover      = ImOnFireSpringsteen.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Bruce Springsteen]]\n| album      = [[Born in the U.S.A.]]\n| B-side     = Johnny Bye Bye\n| released   = February 6, 1985\n| format     = [[7\" single]]\n| recorded   = May 11, 1982\n| studio     = [[Power Station (recording studio)|The Power Station]]\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n* [[Soft rock]]\n}}\n| length     = 2:37\n| label      = [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n| writer     = Bruce Springsteen\n| producer   = {{flatlist|\n* [[Jon Landau]]\n* [[Chuck Plotkin]]\n* Bruce Springsteen\n* [[Steven Van Zandt]]\n}}\n| prev_title = [[Born in the U.S.A. (song)|Born in the U.S.A.]]\n| prev_year  = 1984\n| next_title = [[Glory Days (Bruce Springsteen song)|Glory Days]]\n| next_year  = 1985\n| misc       = {{Extra track listing\n | album  = Born in the U.S.A.\n | type   = single\n | tracks = {{Born in the U.S.A. tracks}}\n}}\n{{Audio sample\n | type = single\n | file = I'm on Fire by Bruce Springsteen.ogg\n}}\n}}\n\"'''I'm on Fire'''\" is a song written and performed by American [[Heartland rock|rock]] performer [[Bruce Springsteen]]. Released in 1985, it was the fourth single from his album ''[[Born in the U.S.A.]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soundonsound.com/sos/mar10/articles/classictracks_0310.htm|title=Bruce Springsteen \u2018Born In The USA\u2019 &ndash; Classic Tracks|accessdate=March 4, 2012|author=Richard Buskin|publisher=[[Sound on Sound]]|date=March 2010|quote=Recorded with Max Weinberg and Roy Bittan, this moodily atmospheric, synth-based rockabilly track would be added to the album and released as its fourth single.}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\"I'm on Fire\" was first recorded in January 1982 during the first wave of ''Born in the U.S.A.'' sessions, but the album version and the single was cut on May 11, 1982 at [[Power Station (recording studio)|The Power Station]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Heylin |first1=Clinton |title=Song By Song |date=2012 |publisher=Penguin |location=London |url=https://www.penguin.com/ |accessdate=22 August 2019}}</ref> This took place in impromptu fashion when Springsteen started making up a slow tune on guitar for some lyrics he had, some of which had been written for \"Spanish Eyes\", which would later surface on ''[[The Promise (Bruce Springsteen album)|The Promise]]'', and drummer [[Max Weinberg]] and keyboardist [[Roy Bittan]], hearing it for the first time, created an accompaniment on the spot.  The result was a moody number that merges a soft [[rockabilly]] beat, lyrics built around [[sexual tension]], and [[synthesizer]]s into an effective whole; it was one of the first uses of that instrument in Springsteen's music.\n\nThe song peaked at No. 6 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] pop singles charts in early 1985.  It was the fourth of a [[List of Billboard Hot 100 chart achievements and milestones#Most top ten singles from one album|record-tying seven Top 10 hit singles]] to be released from ''Born in the U.S.A.'' The single also reached No. 1 in [[Netherlands|the Netherlands]] for 3 weeks in July and August 1985, while two other Springsteen singles (\"[[Dancing in the Dark (Bruce Springsteen song)|Dancing in the Dark]]\" and \"[[Born in the U.S.A. (song)|Born in the U.S.A.]]\") were also in the top ten. This marked the first time for an artist to have as many as three singles inside the Dutch top ten since [[The Beatles]] did so in 1965.<ref>[https://www.hitdossier.nl/top40/1985/week-29 Dutch Top 40, 20 July 1985]</ref>\n\nUnlike the first three singles from the album, no [[remixes]] were made for \"I'm on Fire\" (nor were any made for any of the subsequent singles released).\n\n==Music video==\nThe [[music video]] for the song was shot in March 1985 in [[Los Angeles]], and was directed by filmmaker [[John Sayles]].  Unlike the previous videos from the album, the video was not a performance clip, but rather a dramatic interpretation of the song's themes.\n\nIn it, Springsteen plays a [[working class]] [[automobile mechanic]] with an attractive, married, very well-to-do, mostly unseen female customer who brings her vintage [[Ford Thunderbird]] in for frequent servicing, always requesting that he does the work.  She leaves a small bunch of keys with him when she leaves in her car, possibly including house keys implying that she wishes to start an [[affair]] with him, but declines his offer to bring the car out to her house when it's ready.  Later that night, he drives the car up to her mansion high in the hills above the city.  He looks to a second floor window with the light on and is about to ring the bell, when he thinks better of it and drops her keys in the mailbox next to the door.  He smiles wistfully and walks away down towards the city lights below.<ref>{{cite video | people = Bruce Springsteen  |date = 1986  | title = I'm on Fire   | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lrpXArn3hII  | medium = Videotape | publisher = [[Sony BMG]] }}</ref>\n\nThe video began airing in mid-April, received extensive [[MTV]] airplay, and later in the year won the [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Male Video]].\n\n==Track listing==\n# \"I'm on Fire\" \u2013 2:36\n# \"Johnny Bye Bye\" (Springsteen, [[Chuck Berry]]) \u2013 1:50\n\nThe B-side of the single, \"Johnny Bye Bye\" - Just before he was sentenced to three years for violating the Mann Act in 1962, [[Chuck Berry]] wrote \"Bye Bye Johnny\", a sequel to \"[[Johnny B. Goode]]\", where a mother sent her musician son off to Hollywood to be a star. \"She drew out all her money from the Southern Trust, and put her little boy aboard the Greyhound Bus\" It wasn't a big hit for Chuck, but Bruce decided to use those lines in 1981, for a new song that used most of the lyrics from Come On Let's Go Tonight, calling it \"Johnny Bye-Bye\". Springsteen had first started performing it in 1981 at the tail end of [[The River Tour]].  It was then recorded in April 1982 during the \"Electric Nebraska\" sessions. The official version was recorded on January 4, 1983 at Thrill Hill West, Los Angeles, CA, and one of the mixes was released on February 6, 1985, as the B-side to \"I'm On Fire\". The song appeared on preliminary song lists for inclusion on what would become ''Born in the U.S.A.'' but was ultimately left off the final album. A 4-track single was released\n\n==Live performance history==\n\"I'm on Fire\" was performed only sporadically at the start of the [[Born in the U.S.A. Tour]], but a couple of months later, it settled into a regular place in the middle of the second set.  It was usually preceded by a long musical introduction, during which Springsteen spoke about not being able to sleep at night when he was young and his parents were struggling and the house was cold.  The song was also given an extended coda of Springsteen's moans against waves of synthesizer.  Such a rendition from an August 19, 1985 performance at [[Giants Stadium]] is included on the ''[[Live/1975-85]]'' box set, but with the spoken part of the introduction edited out.\n\nIn some cases, red lighting from stage floor focused on Springsteen's face was used to further accentuate the song.  On the [[Tunnel of Love Express]], the song was still a regular.  On the [[Human Rights Now! Tour]], Springsteen conducted crowd sing-alongs during the chorus and coda parts.  After some appearances on the [[Bruce Springsteen and the \"Other Band\" Tour|\"Other Band\" Tour]], the song went into a long retirement, not emerging again until occasional performances on 2005's solo [[Devils & Dust Tour]], when he performed it on [[banjo]] with the red lighting back.\n\nBetween 1999 and 2008, the song was only performed on eight occasions with the E Street Band: once on the Reunion Tour (June 17, 1999, Bremen), once on The Rising Tour (April 18, 2003, Ottawa) and six times on the Magic Tour. The song has made surprise return on a semi-regular basis during the European leg of the 2009 Working on a Dream tour. As of November 2009, it has been performed live 245 times.\n\n==Live cover performances==\n* [[Big Country]] included a recorded live cover of the song on their 1996 album ''[[Eclectic (Big Country album)|Eclectic]]''.\n* [[Tori Amos]] covered the song in concert and on the television program and CD release ''[[VH1]] Crossroads'' in 1996.\n* [[Heather Nova]] is known to perform a [[Folk music|folk]] style cover of the song at her live shows, often at the end of the set. It can be heard as the last track of her 2000 live album ''[[Wonderlust]]''. She also performed the song as a duet with [[Sarah McLachlan]] during [[Lilith Fair]].\n* [[Electrelane]] has covered the song live. It appears as a B-side on the ''On Parade'' single and their 2006 compilation album ''[[Singles, B-Sides & Live]].\n* [[Bat For Lashes]] also covered the song live and included it as a bonus track on her 2006 debut album ''Fur and Gold''.\n* [[Jack's Mannequin]] did a cover of the song for AP on April 10, 2007 and have covered the song at numerous live shows.\n* [[Marissa Nadler]] also covered the song during numerous tours.\n* [[Sara Bareilles]] covered this song in April 2009 when she was in New York City for her three shows at Joe's Pub during her Gravity tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brucespringsteen.net/news/hanginout.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110608214538/http://www.brucespringsteen.net/news/hanginout.html|archivedate=2011-06-08 |title=Hangin' On E Street: brucespringsteen.net |publisher=Bruce Springsteen |date= |accessdate=2012-02-24}}</ref> It was consequently included on a 7-song live EP from this tour, distributed for free in early 2010 via her website.\n* [[Ben Harper]] and [[Jennifer Nettles]] performed the song in tribute at the 2009 Kennedy Center Honors.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kennedy-center.org/programs/specialevents/honors/index.cfm |title=The Kennedy Center Honors |publisher=Kennedy-center.org |date=2011-12-27 |access-date=2012-02-24 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120319194353/http://www.kennedy-center.org/programs/specialevents/honors/index.cfm |archive-date=2012-03-19 |df= }}</ref>\n*[[Born Ruffians]] performed the song live at The Loft At UCSD on September 20, 2010. Frontman Luke Lalonde also performed the song for [[The Fader]].<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q7uC727lc_0 |title=FADER TV: At The Bar With Southern Comfort: Born Ruffians, \"I'm On Fire\" |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=2012-02-24}}</ref>\n*[[Matt Andersen]] performed this song on his live album ''Live at Liberty Hotel''. This album was recorded in 2007.\n*[[Philip Quast]] performed part of the song with \"Every Breath You Take\" in 2002, as part of his \"Live at the Donmar\" showcase and subsequent album.\n*[[Tegan and Sara]] have performed part of this song as a live [[medley (music)|medley]] with their song \"Not Tonight\" at several shows in 2012 and 2013.<ref>{{cite web|author=Appleford,Steve|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/tegan-and-sara-explore-new-territory-in-l-a-show-20130202|title=Tegan and Sara Explore New Territory in L.A. Show |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=2013-02-02|accessdate=2013-07-01}}</ref>\n*[[Barry Gibb]] performed it as a part of the setlist of the Mythology Tour in the US, as a thank you to Springsteen who had performed a version of \"Stayin' Alive\" in [[Brisbane]], the childhood place of the brothers Gibb in Australia.\n*[[Lorde]] covered the song as part of a mash-up with her own song \"[[Pure Heroine|400 Lux]]\" in select concerts on her [[Melodrama World Tour]] in 2018.\n*[[Soccer Mommy]] covered the song during her \"Clean\" Tour in 2018.\n*[[John Mayer]] covered the song as a bonus track from the album ''[[Battle Studies (album)|Battle Studies]].\n*[[Gang of Youths]] covered the song during their 2018 US Tour.''\n*[[Chromatics (band)|Chromatics]] covered the song on their EP ''I'm On Fire'', and have performed it at numerous shows on tour.\n\n==Chart performance==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Country\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Australia ([[ARIA Charts|ARIA]])\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|12\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders|1|artist=Bruce Springsteen|song=I'm on Fire|accessdate=2017-12-31}}\n|-\n|Canada ([[RPM (magazine)|RPM]])\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|12\n|-\n|Finland ([[Suomen virallinen lista]])<ref>{{cite book | first= Jake | last= Nyman |year= 2005 | title=Suomi soi 4: Suuri suomalainen listakirja | edition= 1st | publisher=Tammi | location= Helsinki| isbn=  951-31-2503-3| language= Finnish }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|9\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch40|1|year=1985|week=29|accessdate=2017-12-31}}\n<!--\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radio538.nl/web/show/id=44685/chartid=5985 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070617084028/http://www.radio538.nl/web/show/id%3D44685/chartid%3D5985 |archive-date=2007-06-17 |title=De Nederlandse Top 40, week 29, 1985 |access-date=2008-03-01 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n-->\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch100|1|artist=Bruce Springsteen|song=I'm on Fire|accessdate=2017-12-31}}\n|-\n|New Zealand ([[Recorded Music NZ]])\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|10\n|-\n|United Kingdom ([[The Official Charts Company]])\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|5\n|-\n|U.S. ''Billboard'' Hot 100\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|6\n|-\n|U.S. ''Billboard'' [[Hot Adult Contemporary Tracks]].<ref>{{cite book |title= Top Adult Contemporary: 1961-2001|last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=2002 |publisher=Record Research |page=229}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|6\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year-end chart (1985) !! Rank\n|-\n|[[Billboard Year-End Hot 100 singles of 1985|US Top Pop Singles (''Billboard'')]]<ref>{{cite magazine|date=December 28, 1985 |title=1985 The Year in Music & Video: Top Pop Singles |page=T-21 |journal=Billboard |volume=97 |issue=52 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|82\n|}\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2014)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br/>position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Germany|95|artist=Bruce Springsteen|song=I'm On Fire}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n'''Works cited'''\n{{Refbegin}}\n* ''Born in the U.S.A. The World Tour'' (tour booklet, 1985), Tour chronology.\n* [[Dave Marsh|Marsh, Dave]].  ''Glory Days: Bruce Springsteen in the 1980s''.  Pantheon Books, 1987.  {{ISBN|0-394-54668-7}}.\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://brucebase.wikidot.com/stats:born-in-the-usa-studio-sessions Brucebase recording sessions history]\n\n{{Bruce Springsteen}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:I'm On Fire}}\n[[Category:Bruce Springsteen songs]]\n[[Category:1984 songs]]\n[[Category:1985 singles]]\n[[Category:Dutch Top 40 number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Single Top 100 number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Ultratop 50 Singles (Flanders) number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Bruce Springsteen]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Jon Landau]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records singles]]\n[[Category:Music videos directed by John Sayles]]\n[[Category:MTV Video Music Award for Best Male Video]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Bruce Springsteen]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Steven Van Zandt]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Chuck Plotkin]]\n[[Category:American soft rock songs]]\n[[Category:Songs about sexuality]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = I'm on Fire\n| cover      = ImOnFireSpringsteen.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Bruce Springsteen]]\n| album      = [[Born in the U.S.A.]]\n| B-side     = Johnny Bye Bye\n| released   = February 6, 1985\n| format     = [[7\" single]]\n| recorded   = May 11, 1982\n| studio     = [[Power Station (recording studio)|The Power Station]]\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n* [[Soft rock]]\n}}\n| length     = 2:37\n| label      = [[Columbia 